      <hedline>
        <hl1>Fields of Oil, From Iraq to Alaska</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Mark Whitenton (National Assn of Manufacturers) says Paul Krugman's assessment of potential for world oil crisis is effective argument for opening Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to exploration (Apr 9 Op-Ed column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If a case for opening the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to oil and gas exploration has ever been made more effectively than Paul Krugman's April 9 column, ''The Third Oil Crisis?,'' I haven't read it.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>If a case for opening the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to oil and gas exploration has ever been made more effectively than Paul Krugman's April 9 column, ''The Third Oil Crisis?,'' I haven't read it.</p>
        <p>Until renewable energy technologies are further refined and become economically viable, the inescapable truth is that our economy will continue to run primarily on fossil fuels. And until we expand our own domestic production of those fuels, our economy will be vulnerable to the whims of Iraq, Venezuela and others.</p>
        <p>MARK WHITENTON  V.P., Resources &amp; Environment  Natl. Assn. of Manufacturers  Washington, April 9, 2002</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
